<div id="review_3323435844" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3323435844" />
    <a title="Greta" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/111566858-greta"><img alt="Greta" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1586844759p2/111566858.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3323435844?book_show_action=true">May 08, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Greta" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Greta" href="/user/show/111566858-greta">Greta</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/19031590-einstein">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/111566858-greta?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3323435844" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5621282380964829981">“Imagination is more important than knowledge. Knowledge is limited. Imagination encircles the world”<br/><br/>This is the second biography I read by Walter Isaacson which is why I already was familiar with his excruciating love for details. His research has as expected impressive range and rather than just being told what Einstein did when and why, you are basically offered a psychological profile and analysis of the man. And just as with Steve Jobs you realize that Einstein was anything but a simple per</span>
  <span id="freeText5621282380964829981" style="display:none">“Imagination is more important than knowledge. Knowledge is limited. Imagination encircles the world”<br /><br />This is the second biography I read by Walter Isaacson which is why I already was familiar with his excruciating love for details. His research has as expected impressive range and rather than just being told what Einstein did when and why, you are basically offered a psychological profile and analysis of the man. And just as with Steve Jobs you realize that Einstein was anything but a simple personality. Instead he is viewed as a kind of inherent rebel. <br /><br />Einstein is described as an extremely insolent personality who possessed a strong sense of creativity and independence that helped him to succeed as a physicist but also almost quashed his career as a young man.<br /><br />Some interesting facts about him:<br /><br />1. He wasn’t a bad student as often claimed. He scored high scores in school but was quite lazy! and criticized the mechanical discipline of schools.<br /><br />2. No one knows what happened to his first daughter. From papers he wrote it got clear that he had one, who apparently got sick but no one knows what happened to her. Officially she doesn’t exist and Einstein never cleared up the mystery.<br /><br />3. Einstein needed nine years to find a job in academia. His rebellious personality and his habit to skip classes left him with bad recommendations from his professors when graduating, which made it extremely hard for him to get his first job.<br /><br />4. He offered his wife his Nobel price as part of their divorce settlement, bevor he even won it. He never got the Nobel Price for what he is famous for: the special relativity but for the photoelectric effect instead.<br /><br />5. The FBI spied on him for decades and he urged the building of the atomic bomb. Even though he wasn’t part of the Manhattan program and highly pacifistic, he wrote a letter to Franklin D. Roosevelt to conduct atomic research. Later he deeply regretted his participation and became a proponent of nuclear disarmament. <br /><br />6. He was asked to become president of Israel.<br />He turned this offer away because he said that he was unfit in concern of social or technical skills and knowledge to hold an official office. Even though he started to identify a lot with being Jewish during the Second World War, he did not believe in a personal God, a view which he described as naïve. Neither did he believe in life after death. Einstein believed the problem of God was a question that could not be answered with yes and no. Therefore he didn’t call himself an atheist either but rather a religious nonbeliever or agnostic and also rejected party politics.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5621282380964829981" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


